{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9749e22c-2b47-4b7c-b603-43155ba7fd5a","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool (must be an `Exe`).\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n- If you have a `README.md`, include it with:\n  ```xml\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n  ```\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. Would you like me to create or update your `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b623c164-223c-4fce-ab10-315e1ea557f4","outputTokens":536,"requestId":"1584:301230:317CE6C:36304A5:69FBE61D"},"id":"a3c113ec-7c64-4bb2-817c-2b84f414fa0a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:08:56.008Z","parentId":"5577a104-5cf4-4dba-8d2b-898acb72fa88"}
